0.0.2 Q2

#t-test
shapiro.test(dd$GRate[dd$diet == 'Natural'])
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  dd$GRate[dd$diet == "Natural"]
## W = 0.95985, p-value = 0.307
shapiro.test(dd$GRate[dd$diet == 'Artificial'])
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  dd$GRate[dd$diet == "Artificial"]
## W = 0.94863, p-value = 0.1553
#equal variances test
var.test(dd$GRate[dd$diet == 'Natural'], dd$GRate[dd$diet == 'Artificial'])
## 
##  F test to compare two variances
## 
## data:  dd$GRate[dd$diet == "Natural"] and dd$GRate[dd$diet == "Artificial"]
## F = 0.50946, num df = 29, denom df = 29, p-value = 0.07445
## alternative hypothesis: true ratio of variances is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.2424828 1.0703634
## sample estimates:
## ratio of variances 
##          0.5094553
#both seem normally distributed and variances appear equal
#could proceed with a student's t-test

0.0.3 Q3

#could proceed with a student's t-test
# H0 = no significant difference in growth rates
t.test(dd$GRate ~ dd$diet, var.equal = TRUE)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  dd$GRate by dd$diet
## t = -1.3259, df = 58, p-value = 0.1901
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group Artificial and group Natural is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.6319362  0.1283495
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Artificial    mean in group Natural 
##                 9.794133                10.045927

t-statistic = how many standard deviations the sample means are apart df = sample sizes and assumption of equal variances

t= -1.3259: mean of the Artificial diet group is less than that of the Natural diet p = 0.1901: H0 not rejected, no significant difference in growth rates 95% CI: (-0.613962, 0.1283495): includes 0, supports that no signf. difference

0.0.5 Q5

anova(m1)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: GRate
##           Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
## diet       1  0.951 0.95100  1.7579 0.1901
## Residuals 58 31.377 0.54098

comparing t-test and anova: - they are mathematically equivalent when comparing means of groups - p-values (0.1901) are therefore the same - df=1: one factor (diet) with two levels - df=58: 60 observations minus two parameters - F(1, 58) = 1.7579, p = 0.1901: no statistically significant difference in the mean growth rates -> diet type did not have a measurable impact

plot(tukey, las = 1)

- ASGM differs from all treatments (p < 0.01).
- Sstat differs from Sexpo (p = 0.0016).
- No difference: Sexpo vs Sdecl, Sstat vs Sdecl (p > 0.05).
- ASGM and Sstat show the largest differences.

0.0.12 Q17, 18, 19

#slopes were not parallel, interaction term!
m4 <- lm(beat_rate ~ temp * Facclimatisation_temp, data = dd3)
summary(m4)

  • effect of temperature on beat_rate varies depending on the acclimatisation temperature

  • explains why lines in facet plot not parallel

0.0.13 Q20

autoplot(m4)

- no major violations regression assumptions - slight heteroscedasticity at higher fitted values - minor non-normality - no strong outliers

0.0.14 Q21

  • Linear model with interaction term tested effects of temp and Facclimatisation_temp on beat_rate
  • Significant interaction( p < 0.001) -> Effect of temp on beat rate varies by acclimatisation temp
  • Main effects significant (p < 0.001) but not interpretable alone due to interaction
  • High model fit (Adjusted R² = 0.9622)
  • Residual diagnostics: slight heteroscedasticity, no major violations
  • Beat rate increases with temp, but rate of increase depends on acclimatisation temp
  • Next step: Separate regressions for each acclimatisation group may be necessary
